            </origination>
        </did>
        <bioghist id="ref35">
            <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
            <p>The Readers Feast opened in 1983 at 529 Farmington Avenue in Hartford, Connecticut. As the first independent, progressive bookstore in the area, Readers Feast sold books ranging from traditional fiction, cookbooks and children’s books to the latest feminist, gay and lesbian, Spanish language and progressive political titles. Their café (opening a few months later) had gourmet menu featuring light lunches and dinners, home-baked desserts and freshly brewed coffee, cappuccino, and espresso.</p>
            <p>Thirty local people pooled their resources to invest in the bookstore including several professors from the University Of Connecticut School Of Social Work, attorneys from the Connecticut Civil Liberties Union, community organizers from local groups, an artist and a gourmet cook. Carolyn Gabel, president and co-manager, was a former professor at the UCONN School of Social Work and Tollie Miller, co-manager and investor, were the owners for 12 years. Their goal was to create a community resource with books that represent different points of view and cultural perspectives and a safe, comfortable space for all kinds of people. Small events also occurred at the store such as readings, musical performances, small theatre presentation, and political meetings or talks. The arrival of the large national bookstore chain’s resulted in reduced sales. The struggle to run the bookstore during this difficult period resulted in Carolyn and Tollie stepping down in 1995. Under the new management of Barbara Mase, Roberta Collins, and Valerie de Palma, the bookstore continued to operate until 2007.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <processinfo id="ref39">
            <head>Processing Information note</head>
            <p>Materials in box 2 was added in October 2015 and was separated from materials donated by Carolyn Gable. It makes sense to keep these materials together since Tollie Miller and Carolyn Gable were co-managers of the bookstore for 13 years.</p>
        </processinfo>
        <scopecontent id="ref33">
            <head>Scope and Contents note</head>
            <p>The collection consists of subject files, records of the bookstore, correspondence, notes, flyers, printed materials, and photographs, which illustrate activities of the bookstore..</p>
        </scopecontent>
